## Taco — Visual Feedback Tool

You have access to the Taco MCP server, which connects you to visual
comments left by the user on their localhost web app via the Taco
Chrome extension.

### Available tools

1. `mcp_taco_get_comments` — Retrieve all pending (unresolved) comments.
   Each comment includes:
   - `text` — the user's comment
   - `selector` — CSS selector of the annotated element
   - `url` — the page URL where the comment was left
   - `screenshot` — base64 screenshot of the annotated area (if available)

2. `mcp_taco_mark_resolved` — Mark a comment as resolved by its ID.
   Call this after you have addressed a comment.

3. `mcp_taco_get_all_comments` — Retrieve all comments including
   resolved ones. Use this to see the full history.

4. `mcp_taco_action_comment` — Mark a comment as in-progress (actioned)
   before starting work on it. Prevents duplicate pickup across sessions.
### Workflow

When the user asks you to check comments or fix UI issues:

1. Call `mcp_taco_get_comments` to retrieve pending comments
2. For each comment, use the `selector` and `screenshot` to locate
   the element in the codebase and understand the issue
3. Make the necessary code changes
4. Call `mcp_taco_mark_resolved` with the comment ID after addressing it
5. Summarise what you changed for each comment

### Important

- Always check for pending comments when the user mentions Taco,
  feedback, or visual issues
- Use the screenshot to understand visual context — it shows exactly
  what the user sees
- The CSS selector identifies the specific DOM element the user
  annotated — use it to find the corresponding component in code

